title: Shell Scripting
description: I bought this for my year-of-Linux to get up to speed with and fluent at programming at the shell level, useful scripts and being able to easily manipulate text.
notes:
- chap1: background
	- software tools principles
		- do one thing well
		- process lines of text, not binary
		- use regular expressions
		- default to standard I/O
		- don't be chatty
			- no "starting process", "almost done", or "finished processing" messages
		- generate the same output format accepted as input
			- enables pipelining
		- let someone else do the hard part
			- use 90% other tools
			- map them together
		- consider the general use of tools you make
			- can they be tweaked to be useful for others

title: Seven Databases in Seven Weeks
description: This is a good book to read away from the computer to get to know seven databases at a higher level, how they work, their advantages and disadvantages and what kinds of projects they are best used for. The seven include the SQL database PostgreSQL, the key-value Redis as well as the key-value cloud database DynamoDB column-oriented HBase, the two NoSQL databases MongoDB and CouchDB, and the graph database Neo4J.

title: Practical Jamstack

The author writes in a fun, casual style as if a friend where telling you about Jamstack, light reading.
